SIMPLE: sardonic
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Sardonic
<hw>Sar*don"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>sardonique</ets>, L. <ets>sardonius</ets>, Gr. <?/, <?/, perhaps
fr. <?/ to grin like a dog, or from a certain plant of
<ets>Sardinia</ets>, Gr. <?/, which was said to screw up the face of the
eater.]</ety> <def>Forced; unnatural; insincere; hence, derisive,
mocking, malignant, or bitterly sarcastic; -- applied only to a laugh,
smile, or some facial semblance of gayety.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Where strained, <qex>sardonic</qex> smiles are glozing still,⟦br⟧
And grief is forced to laugh against her will.</q> <rj><qau>Sir H.
Wotton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The scornful, ferocious, <qex>sardonic</qex> grin of a bloody
ruffian.</q> <rj><qau>Burke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>Sardonic grin</b></col> <it>or</it>
<col><b>Sardonic laugh</b></col></mcol>, <cd>an old medical term for a
spasmodic affection of the muscles of the face, giving it an appearance
of laughter.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sardonic</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Sardonic
<hw>Sar*don"ic</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of, pertaining to, or
resembling, a kind of linen made at Colchis.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sardonyx</ent>⟦br⟧
